Super stoked to share this one with y’all!! I’ve been working on refining this design behind the scenes for a couple of months now, and after much prototyping and many tweaks, this is the first one that I’m ready to share and release to the public. 

This is by far the most technically advanced design that I’ve made and I couldn’t be more excited to share it with you and to keep making more! The color I used on this one is karmaline from @northstarglass 💕

The function on this design is insane. The two uptakes create a blooping effect that feels crazy while you hit it, while the return dumps bubbles back into the base. Talk about some active bubble dumping technology! Hopping to have some more available soon so you can try it yourself! 

This piece is part of an order that will be going to @habitual_glass, but I think I’ll be bringing it to glass Vegas if you’d like to see it in person! 

Let me know what you think of the new design and if you have any ideas for what I should call them!

Excited to properly release this new design that I’ve been working on! I’m calling this form the Hypogeum (pronounced “hy-puh-jee-uhm) 

The silhouette of this design is simplistic and easy to understand at a glance. beneath the surface however, the nature of the internal chambers can be difficult to comprehend and may even illicit feelings of confusion. This concept of a hidden complexity beneath an unassuming exterior has inspired me to come up with this name for the design. 

Coming from the Greek words “Hypo” (Under) and “Gaia” (Earth), Hypogeum is a term usually used in reference to an underground chamber built into ancient structures. The purpose of this chamber is typically a temple or a tomb. 

I’m excited to keep exploring this concept and design, and plan to keep improving it as time goes on! My books are open for customs and wholesale orders, hit me up! Thanks for everyone’s support over the years! It means the world! 

Huge shout out to @zach.borovision and @boro.vision for throwing this edit together!
